---
import Layout from "../../../layouts/LayoutDue.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="About"
  description="Why Due exists, and the principles behind how it's built."
>
  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
      <h1>A bill reminder, and nothing more</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Due was built to solve one problem: knowing a bill is coming before it's late. Not
        budgeting, not net worth tracking, not a linked bank account, just a reliable nudge before
        each due date.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="content">
    <div class="wrap legal-content">
      <h2>Why it exists</h2>
      <p>
        Most bill and budgeting apps ask for a lot up front, an account, a linked bank, permission
        to categorize every transaction, in exchange for a reminder that could have been a simple
        local notification. Due starts from the other direction: what's the smallest app that
        reliably solves "remind me before this is due," with nothing extra attached to it.
      </p>

      <h2>How it's built</h2>
      <p>
        Due is a native iOS app. Every bill you add, the name, amount, due date, and how often it
        repeats, is stored directly on your device. When a bill is recurring, paying it rolls the
        due date forward to the next cycle automatically, correctly handling short months so a bill
        due on the 31st doesn't quietly drift to the wrong date over time. Reminders are scheduled
        as local notifications, and you can mark a bill paid straight from the notification without
        opening the app.
      </p>

      <h2>What it isn't</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>It isn't a budgeting app. It doesn't categorize spending or track net worth.</li>
        <li>It doesn't connect to your bank or any financial institution.</li>
        <li>It doesn't have an account system, because there's nothing to sync.</li>
        <li>It doesn't collect analytics on how you use it.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Supporting development</h2>
      <p>
        Due is free to use. If it's useful to you, there's an optional tip inside the app a
        one-time purchase through Apple's App Store, entirely separate from your bill data. It
        changes nothing about how the app works either way.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .page-hero {
    background: var(--cream);
    padding: 72px 0 56px;
  }

  .eyebrow {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 12px;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    color: var(--forest);
    margin-bottom: 16px;
  }

  .page-hero h1 {
    font-size: clamp(30px, 4vw, 42px);
    margin-bottom: 18px;
    max-width: 20ch;
  }

  .lede {
    font-size: 17px;
    color: var(--ink);
    max-width: 56ch;
  }

  .content {
    padding: 64px 0 96px;
  }

  .legal-content {
    max-width: 680px;
  }
</style>